body:
The present commenting plugin uses `/* %s */` for C/C++ comments. This has a problem when commenting commented code. For example

```
int a = 1;
/*int b = 2;*/
int c = 3;
````

when commented together by selecting using 'V' would become

```
/*int a = 1;*/
/*/*int b = 2;*/*/
/*int c = 3;*/
````

which is not valid C/C++ code. This commit changes the commit string to `// %s` which solves this problem.

Closes #29079

comment_regular_data.body:
Here's what I propose to move this forward:

* for any ftplugin in Lua that sets the commentstring for a C-type language, change to `// %s`: `c`, `d`, `cs`, `indent`
* for any ftplugin that includes a `runtime! ftplugin/c.vim`, add a separate ftplugin in Lua that sets the commentstring explicitly (as `// %s` if it's C-type: `objc`, `ch`, or the actually correct commentstring if it isn't: `xdefaults`, `xs`, `css`);
* `cpp` can be left as-is (to keep the link for user plugins);
* do not touch any other ftplugins; those are left for Vim to fix (if you are motivated enough, you can contact each maintainer and notify them, but many are unfortunately abandonware).

(All these should use padding if the syntax allows it. Don't worry about consistency.)

And to be clear: the goal here is _not_ to have "all C-like languages have the commentstring `// %s`"! The only goals are 
1. have C itself have `// %` (because that is the what we use in our own C code);
2. fix the fallout from this breaking change by explicitly setting all derived commentstrings correctly(!) (if at all reasonable, to the same value Vim uses -- because changes to _those_ should go through upstream).

